  <div class="row">
      <div class="col-lg-12">
          <h2 class="page-header">Context</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="col-md-6 content">
        <p>
          Most farmers in developing countries practice rain-fed agriculture. Not enough rain means plants don’t produce a harvest while too much rain can kill growing crops. To mitigate heavy rainfall or drought spell risks, weather insurance represents a cheap and transparent risk management solution, mostly intended to insure smallholders’ farmers against natural hazards, water-related perils, crops failure and climate risk.
          Yet, the poor rain gauge network and the short historical time series across sub-Saharan Africa prevent a proper risk assessment and an accurate insurance design. If the spatial and temporal variability of rainfall is not accurately estimated, only areas covered by a dense rain gauge network with long histories can benefit from insurance coverage.
        </p>
      </div>
